{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17507628","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17507628"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T11:55:10+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T11:55:10+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2648"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2648","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2648"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.17,0.53,0.18,0.04,0.08]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2648"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"102299"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2648","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2648"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2648"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"84763"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"6"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"3189"},{"type":"tags","id":"6275"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"3061"},{"type":"contributions","id":"3069"},{"type":"contributions","id":"18447"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35691"},{"type":"contributions","id":"48797"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"102299","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/102299"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 83-year-old woman is admitted to hospital after sustaining a fall at home earlier today. She reports severe left hip pain and has been unable to mobilise since the incident. Plain radiographs confirm a left neck of femur fracture and she is listed for surgery on the following morning. For pain control she receives subcutaneous morphine, which provides good relief.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHer medical history includes mild cognitive impairment, coronary artery disease, and type 2 diabetes. She quit smoking 10 years ago after a 30 pack-year history, does not drink alcohol and does not use recreational drugs.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThat night the intern is asked to review her because nursing staff report new agitation. She has been pulling at intravenous lines and blankets. At review, she is drowsy, disorientated and unable to give a clear history of pain. Initial blood tests, including electrolytes, full blood count and glucose, are within reference limits.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is most likely to be effective in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Start regular haloperidol","Reduce morphine, add paracetamol and ibuprofen","Administer lorazepam","Increase the morphine dose","Change to a fentanyl infusion"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis presentation is consistent with hypoactive\u2013hyperactive fluctuating delirium in a person with several pre-disposing factors including pre-existing cognitive impairment, advanced age, and reduced mobility. Opioid administration is a well-recognised precipitating cause and there is a clear temporal relationship between the morphine dose and the change in cognition. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EReduce morphine, add paracetamol and ibuprofen\u003C/strong\u003E addresses the likely precipitant while ensuring continued analgesia through a multimodal, non-opioid regimen. Such an approach often improves mental status within hours and facilitates safer preparation for surgery. Whilst NSAIDs pose a risk of bleeding pre-operatively, in the given circumstances, the patient must be provided with adequate pain relief and so short-term ibuprofen would be quite reasonable. Regional anaesthesia, such as a femoral nerve block, should also be considered.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EStart regular haloperidol\u003C/strong\u003E can be useful for severe agitation that endangers the person or others, but guidelines recommend treating or removing the underlying cause first. Antipsychotics carry risks of extrapyramidal effects, QT prolongation and stroke, particularly in older adults.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAdminister lorazepam\u003C/strong\u003E is generally avoided in delirium outside alcohol or benzodiazepine withdrawal because benzodiazepines can worsen confusion and oversedation, especially when combined with opioids.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncrease the morphine dose\u003C/strong\u003E would likely exacerbate the delirium given the dose-dependent association between opioids and acute cognitive impairment, without providing additional benefit in a patient who is already pain-free.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EChange to a fentanyl infusion\u003C/strong\u003E substitutes one strong opioid for another and therefore does not remove the precipitating factor; fentanyl has similar central nervous system effects and may further worsen confusion and sedation. It would also require more intensive monitoring in a specialised environment like a high dependency or intensive care unit, both of which would likely aggravate the patient\u0027s delirium. \u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Opioid analgesia is a common, reversible precipitant of delirium in older inpatients.","First-line management of opioid-related delirium is dose reduction and multimodal non-opioid analgesia rather than additional psychoactive drugs."],"references":["Fong HK, Sands LP, Leung JM. The role of postoperative analgesia in delirium and cognitive decline in elderly patients: a systematic review. Anesth Analg. 2006 Apr;102(4):1255-66. doi: 10.1213/01.ane.0000198602.29716.53. PMID: 16551934."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"84763"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2648"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"84763","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/84763"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-05-11T14:03:06+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-05-11T14:03:42+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2648"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"102299"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"6","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/6"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc75","name":"Geriatrics","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"78","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/78"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level III","synonyms":null,"description":"Apply, analyze, evaluate, and create (implementing, organizing, and critiquing information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"3189","links":{"self"